DMCI, Petron, San Miguel, Semirara: Philippine Stocks Preview

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-03-08T00:53:53Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-08/dmci-petron-san-miguel-semirara-philippine-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual price changes in Philippine trading. Stock
symbols are in parentheses, and prices are as of the previous
close, unless stated otherwise.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 0.1 percent to
3,886.48.    MacroAsia Corp. (MAC)  : The provider of in-flight
catering services bought 20,000 shares at 3.05 pesos each, a
stock exchange filing showed. The stock was unchanged at 3.05
pesos.    International Container Terminal Services Inc. (ICT)  :
The largest Philippine operator said full-year profit rose 79
percent to $98.3 million in 2010. Sales increased 25 percent to
$527.1 million from 2009, it said. The company is budgeting $356
million for this year’s capital expenditures, it said. The stock
gained 2.8 percent to 42.95 pesos.    Petron Corp. (PCOR)  : The government asked  oil companies 
to step up oil imports and maintain a minimum 15-day “in-
country” inventory, Energy Secretary Rene Almendras said.
Petron, the largest of two oil refiners in the country, rose 2
percent to 15.60 pesos.    San Miguel Corp. (SMC)  : The largest Philippine food and
drinks company will join in all bidding to privatize government
assets, a stock exchange filing showed. The stock declined 0.9
percent to 170 pesos.    Semirara Mining Corp. (SCC)  : The largest coal producer
will develop the site of a power plant in the province of
Batangas into a so-called “ecozone” to attract clients with
high electricity requirements, a stock exchange filing showed.
Semirara fell 1 percent to 203.80 pesos.  DMCI Holdings Inc. (DMC)  , the nation’s biggest construction company and owner of
Semirara, fell 1 percent to 35.50 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in Manila at 
 isayson@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
